ass="word-wrap-span">WHEN ass="word-wrap-span">KATIE FAHEY (pictured), a ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan resident, founded ass="word-wrap-span">Voters ass="word-wrap-span">Not ass="word-wrap-span">Politicians in 2017, she took aim at gerrymandering—the increasingly potent practice whereby ass="word-wrap-span">Politicians of both parties redraw electoral lines to maximise their party’s advantage. ass="word-wrap-span">After gathering 425,000 signatures to get a redistricting-reform ass="word-wrap-span">amendment on ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan’s 2018 ballot, the organisation overcame opposition from well-funded ass="word-wrap-span">Republican groups and won two court battles that aimed to scrap the proposal. ass="word-wrap-span">Last year, ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan ass="word-wrap-span">Voters ass="word-wrap-span">approved the ass="word-wrap-span">amendment by a 61% majority. ass="word-wrap-span">But on July 30th, on the eve of the commission’s formation, several ass="word-wrap-span">Notable ass="word-wrap-span">Republicans have coalesced to scuttle the plan before it gets off the ground.

In a novel complaint , 15 ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan residents—shepherded by an ass="word-wrap-span">ass="word-wrap-span">affiliate of the ass="word-wrap-span">National ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Redistricting ass="word-wrap-span">Trust, an organisation positioning the ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Party for district-line drawing in the coming decade—are suing to stop the commission in its tracks. By limiting who may serve as commissioners, the plaintiffs say, ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan would be violating the free-speech, free-association and equal-protection rights of hundreds of thousands of its residents. ass="word-wrap-span">Scott ass="word-wrap-span">Walker, the former governor of ass="word-wrap-span">Wisconsin and the organisation’s finance chair, says the commission’s membership rule “punish[es] the people of ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan for exercising those rights—or for being related to someone who has”.

ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">amendment bars anyone who has, in ass="word-wrap-span">The last six years, sought or held elected office or served as a lobbyist or an insider for a political ass="word-wrap-span">Party. ass="word-wrap-span">Their parents, children and spouses are barred from service, too. ass="word-wrap-span">Plaintiffs in ass="word-wrap-span">Daunt v. ass="word-wrap-span">Benson include ass="word-wrap-span">Anthony ass="word-wrap-span">Daunt, a ass="word-wrap-span">Republican lobbyist who has served on ass="word-wrap-span">The governing body of ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Party committee; ass="word-wrap-span">Kathy Berden, ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">GOP’s national committeewoman; Patrick ass="word-wrap-span">Meyers, a political consultant; and Mary Shinkle, once a staffer for a ass="word-wrap-span">Republican congressman and now a county ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Party official. ass="word-wrap-span">These and ass="word-wrap-span">The eleven oass="word-wrap-span">Ther challengers all complain that ass="word-wrap-span">They are ineligible to serve on ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan’s independent redistricting commission. ass="word-wrap-span">They want ass="word-wrap-span">The task of redistricting returned to ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan's legislature, where ass="word-wrap-span">Republicans hold majorities in both houses.

ass="word-wrap-span">Helen ass="word-wrap-span">Norton, a law professor at the ass="word-wrap-span">University of ass="word-wrap-span">Colorado, explains that the ass="word-wrap-span">First ass="word-wrap-span">Amendment bars “unjustified interference with these sorts of political activities” and imposes a “heavy burden” of justification when the government does interfere. ass="word-wrap-span">But she notes that in a less famous portion of the ass="word-wrap-span">Citizens ass="word-wrap-span">United ruling in 2010, the ass="word-wrap-span">Supreme ass="word-wrap-span">Court upheld, by an 8-1 vote, a rule requiring ass="word-wrap-span">advertisers and campaign contriass="word-wrap-span">Butors to publicly disclose their identities. ass="word-wrap-span">This condition may interfere with a donor’s freedom of speech by forcing him to declare his support, ass="word-wrap-span">But it is, the ass="word-wrap-span">Justices held, a justified intrusion. ass="word-wrap-span">Only ass="word-wrap-span">Justice ass="word-wrap-span">Clarence ass="word-wrap-span">Thomas dissented from the ass="word-wrap-span">Court’s view that “the public has an interest in knowing who is speaking about a candidate shortly before an election”.

ass="word-wrap-span">Will ass="word-wrap-span">The district court in ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan find a similarly clear justification behind ass="word-wrap-span">The eligibility rules for ass="word-wrap-span">The nascent redistricting commission? ass="word-wrap-span">The crux of ass="word-wrap-span">The matter, Ms ass="word-wrap-span">Norton explains, is ass="word-wrap-span">The “tightness of ass="word-wrap-span">The fit” between ass="word-wrap-span">The conditions and ass="word-wrap-span">The commission’s goals. “Is ass="word-wrap-span">There a strong relationship between ass="word-wrap-span">The two, between ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan’s chosen means and its chosen ends?”, she asks. Yes, she says, since “partisan leaders, officials and candidates are likely to have especially strong partisan interests”. ass="word-wrap-span">But ass="word-wrap-span">The fit is not “perfect”, as oass="word-wrap-span">Ther people not barred by ass="word-wrap-span">The criteria might be highly partisan, too; ass="word-wrap-span">The lawsuit argues ass="word-wrap-span">There is no good reason to think ass="word-wrap-span">That ass="word-wrap-span">The plaintiffs would make ass="word-wrap-span">The commission less impartial than would commissioners “who hold political views ass="word-wrap-span">That are just as strong, or even stronger, ass="word-wrap-span">But do not happen to belong to one of ass="word-wrap-span">The excluded groups”. ass="word-wrap-span">The question is wheass="word-wrap-span">Ther ass="word-wrap-span">The tie between ass="word-wrap-span">The goal of impartiality and ass="word-wrap-span">The no-political-insiders rule is intimate enough. “ass="word-wrap-span">That’s what all ass="word-wrap-span">The fighting ass="word-wrap-span">Will be about”, Ms ass="word-wrap-span">Norton says.

A closer look at ass="word-wrap-span">The lawsuit suggests ass="word-wrap-span">The plaintiffs may face an uphill battle. ass="word-wrap-span">The main ass="word-wrap-span">Supreme ass="word-wrap-span">Court case ass="word-wrap-span">The challengers cite in ass="word-wrap-span">Their favour—a 1990 decision called Rutan v ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Party of ass="word-wrap-span">Illinois —doesn’t quite match up. ass="word-wrap-span">The question in Rutan was wheass="word-wrap-span">Ther ass="word-wrap-span">The state government in ass="word-wrap-span">Illinois could base its hiring and promotion decisions on baldly partisan considerations: how much ass="word-wrap-span">applicants had contributed to ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">Republican ass="word-wrap-span">Party, for example, or wheass="word-wrap-span">Ther local ass="word-wrap-span">Party officials supported ass="word-wrap-span">Them. By a 5-4 vote, ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">Supreme ass="word-wrap-span">Court said this kind of official discrimination against individuals based on political ass="word-wrap-span">Party was a violation of ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">First ass="word-wrap-span">Amendment. ass="word-wrap-span">Patronage systems in which hiring and promotion decisions are a function of “political ass="word-wrap-span">affiliation or support” are “an impermissible infringement on ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">First ass="word-wrap-span">Amendment rights of public employees”.

ass="word-wrap-span">But here is ass="word-wrap-span">The problem with relying on Rutan to strike down ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan’s independent redistricting effort: ass="word-wrap-span">The eligibility rules for commissioners under attack in ass="word-wrap-span">Daunt v ass="word-wrap-span">Benson are not based on viewpoint. ass="word-wrap-span">They are based on activity: recent ass="word-wrap-span">Democratic candidates and party insiders are barred from participation just as ass="word-wrap-span">Their ass="word-wrap-span">Republican counterparts are. ass="word-wrap-span">The disqualification is even-handed and not based on a failure to swear loyalty to any particular political party. ass="word-wrap-span">The rules are based on ass="word-wrap-span">The raass="word-wrap-span">Ther reasonable idea that party insiders are probably not ass="word-wrap-span">The most impartial people to draw fair electoral lines.

ass="word-wrap-span">Rick Hasen, an election-law expert at the ass="word-wrap-span">University of ass="word-wrap-span">California-ass="word-wrap-span">Irvine, says “it would take a big change in ass="word-wrap-span">First ass="word-wrap-span">Amendment doctrine” for the plaintiffs in ass="word-wrap-span">Daunt to succeed. Mr Hasen says an individual judge might buy the argument, but he is “sceptical the position will ultimately prevail”. ass="word-wrap-span">One strong piece of evidence for this view comes in section 5 of Rucho v ass="word-wrap-span">Common ass="word-wrap-span">Cause, the recent decision in which the ass="word-wrap-span">Supreme ass="word-wrap-span">Court said federal judges are unsuited to police partisan gerrymandering. ass="word-wrap-span">Don’t despair, ass="word-wrap-span">Chief ass="word-wrap-span">Justice ass="word-wrap-span">John ass="word-wrap-span">Roberts wrote, as “the states...are ass="word-wrap-span">actively addressing the issue on a number of fronts”, and “in November 2018, voters in ass="word-wrap-span">Colorado and ass="word-wrap-span">Michigan ass="word-wrap-span">approved constitutional ass="word-wrap-span">Amendments creating multimember commissions that will be responsible in whole or in part for creating and approving district maps for congressional and state legislative districts".

ass="word-wrap-span">Would ass="word-wrap-span">Chief ass="word-wrap-span">Justice ass="word-wrap-span">Roberts and ass="word-wrap-span">The four conservative ass="word-wrap-span">Justices who signed his opinion turn around after Rucho and strike down a commission ass="word-wrap-span">They specifically pointed to as a viable way to address warped electoral lines? ass="word-wrap-span">The ass="word-wrap-span">Supreme ass="word-wrap-span">Court has ass="word-wrap-span">acknowledged that extreme partisan gerrymandering is “incompatible with democratic principles”. To seal shut a release valve it has hailed as a solution ass="word-wrap-span">Would be a dramatic reversal—and bode ill for attempts in oass="word-wrap-span">Ther states to buttress ass="word-wrap-span">America's electoral democracy.
